      <hedline>
        <hl1>So Big Oil's Doing Well. That's Good?</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Paul R Verkuil letter disputes Robert A Mosbacher's August 18 Op-Ed article approving of profits being made by oil companies; drawing</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Oil Profits Are Finally Where They Ought to Be,'' by Robert A. Mosbacher (Op-Ed, Aug. 18):</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Oil Profits Are Finally Where They Ought to Be,'' by Robert A. Mosbacher (Op-Ed, Aug. 18):</p>
        <p>Mr. Mosbacher gives a Texas dimension to chutzpah when he praises profits of $20 on a $30 barrel of oil. By  assuming the continued operation of the Organization of Petroleum Exporting Companies, he foresees a bright future.</p>
        <p>Big oil, like any industry, is entitled to market rates of return, not monopoly rents. OPEC is a contrived benchmark that our government should not accept, let alone endorse.</p>
        <p>PAUL R. VERKUIL  New York, Aug. 21, 2000</p>
      </block>
